ition linked to violence. Indeed, if the nihilist is a person who acknowledges no moral or religious authority, then what does stop him from committing any kind of crime? Dostoevsky precisely called attention to this danger: if there is no God and no immortality of the soul, then everything is permitted, even anthropophagy. Nietzsche, too, emphasised, although in different terms, the consequences deriving from the death of God and the collapse of Judeo-Christian morality. This context shaped the way in which philosophers, writers and artists thought about violence, in its different manifestations, during the 20th century. The goal of this interdisciplinary volume is to explore the various modern and contemporary configurations of the link between violence and nihilism as understood by philosophers and artists (in both literature and film).  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aEthik. 4aGewalt. 4aKulturwissenschaften. 4aNihilismus. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh  aViolence, Nihilism, Ethics, Cultural studies.1 aAguiar de Sousa, Luís, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAguiar de Sousa, Luís, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBagge Laustsen, Carsten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiken, Bülent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerraro, Gianfranco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGertz, Nolen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKickasola, Joseph G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLupo, Luca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarmysz, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb